column7: I was guessing
I mostly went by the tests. I did my best to pay attention to what was lighting up and in which order. No strategy beyond that. Mostly following the lights. I didn't see any bugs or errors.
It was kind of hard to figure out the pattern, but it was fun trying.

One hard aspect was that I couldn't turn the device off. Made it more difficult to be sure of where connections were necessarily coming from. Otherwise, it was fairly easy to active a node and see what happened, marking the causality as I saw it occur.

It was hard, because I wasn't sure if clicking on a new circle turned off the one on which I'd previously clicked. Therefore, I wasn't sure if the connection I was seeing was a new one or something that was cycling through from the previous click.
It was a lot of fun.  It was a lot like doing work on one of the wiring boards with springs like when I was a kid.  I just wish i could reset the system when it started doing cascades.
Through Trial and error and general memory. I found it fairly easy.
I just tried to follow the patterns and use my best estimates. I didnt have a real strategy. There appeared to be no bugs or errors.
I just guessed for the most part, was more difficult than I thought it would be.  There were no errors in the testing
Looking at which ones flashed after I clicked one. It was only hard when they all started flashing I couldn't really tell where it was going.

I tested a random point initially and focused to see when other points were triggered. If multiple points triggered from a single press, I then tested the least triggered point on the device. After I was fairly confident with my initial predictions on the connections, I then tried to test points that disproved my guess while also paying close attention to any possible new information. I had no problems with this experiment and it was appropriately challenging paying attention to the multiple points on the device.
I didn't notice any bugs. I really didn't have a strategy. I just went by my gut. Honestly, this was a little hard for me to full understand, but I tried my best.
Just having to watch where they go and do your best.  Was tough on some of them though.

It really to me a while to see exactly what I was supposed to be doing. And I definitely confused myself a few times by clicking the devices too fast, and changing what was originally the correct answer. Thanks, it was pretty fun!
Some of the connections were a bit buggy in that the components would keep blinking even after I clicked on another one. This made it hard to decide which components connected to others. That's it.
I just watched for flashes. The triangles were the easiest, less points obviously. I never  felt like I understood the exercise 100%.

I just watched the order of the lights, and started to notice patterns. I found it a bit difficult to keep track of double connections at times. It was hard to tell if the signal was going back and forth with a lot of these. Some of the 4 figure formations made it feel like I didn't have enough time because the lights would blink for a long time before stopping so I could test another connection.

I worked out where the connections were by trying to take things one click at a time as much as possible, which made it clearer where connections were at the possible risk of giving up a couple of bonuses. I tried not to click another dot until the first chain I started ran out. The hardest ones for me were the 4 dot connections where a chain would go in many directions and make it hard for me to keep track. I didn't see any errors!

I did a trial by error to figure out the connections.  The experiment was buggy in that when one connection would keep running in a cycle, it was hard to track other connections.  Also, the experiment sometimes froze when I clicked \start\" too fast after I clicked \"continue.\"  This happened to me in round 10 and I had to start the experiment all over again
column8: I clicked the buttons slower and that time it did not freeze."

column7: I am surprised i did as well as i did. I had no strategy, and have no idea how i did it!But this was fun and different!
Extremely hard, I just tried my best to spot and mark.

No real strategy, I just tried to watch closely and do one at a time.  Something I noticed, I wouldn't call it a bug but it was something I didn't find very intuitive, was you had to click a very specific distance from the circles to get the arrows to point the right direction.  I found myself having to remove the arrow and click again about half the time because the arrows seemed to have a mind of their own, but it probably just had a very strict range for the direction it thinks you want to point.
it was hard!!!
just tried following the flashing dots

Testing and retesting! following the longer sequences and the ones that were more complicated was hard! The shapes with more sides than the triangle were esp. hard. I don't think that I did it long enough to have a strategy except for the easy ones. If there were bugs, I didn't notice. I'm sure that there were ones that didn't work (the 10%) but while I was doing the tests I couldn't tell. It was after that I went \oh that's what happened\". :)"
I waited for the timing to tell connections. It was moderately difficult.

I used a trial and error method to figure it out and I tried to place the arrows as quickly as possible while a test was running. I found the puzzles with 4 circles to be the most difficult because the tests were often longer and it was harder to find the direction that it was moving. If I found that a circle was going in one direction to another, I would test it to see if it went in both directions of if it moved back to another circle.

I pressed each button and waited a few seconds to see which nodes lit up and I tried to follow their path. No strategy. Not sure if I started thinking a bit differently mid way through but I started doing worse for some reason.
I observe how the lights respond after click on one.  I tried to make the arrows as quickly as possible.  I checked my guess with the tries that I had left.
It was hard to figure some out and some were easy. If multiple bodes lit up after hitting a node I was confused. But if only one lit up then I could figure it out easier.
I honestly just tried my best to go with my intuitive feelings as what to choose.
The two-way connections made it harder. Strategy was starting at the top and working clockwise.
I was pretty confused when the connections started bouncing all over the place
I just used my own judgement by following the tips given to me.
just click and see what happens next
I tried each one.  I had trouble when the movements were quick and went back and forth.  Some were easy, some were really hard.  It was fun, thanks.  No bugs.
It was difficult I couldn't always tell if they were continuing connections or connections from the node I was testing.

I clicked on each one to try and make my best guess. I wish there was a way to stop the connections so you could test each one individually. The ones that connect both ways are really tricky to detect when you can't stop it going.
First try on any one was a guess then I narrowed down behaviour from there.
I didn't understand the game for the first several tries. I'm still not sure I really understood what I was doing. I would click on a bubble and try to follow where the connections were made.
I looked at the times at which yellow lights appeared. I found it easy to work out where the connections were. No. No.
it was really easy. the connections were also easy.
I observed how the interactions occurred and made my judgement from that. It was fun and a little challenging.
No bugs or problems. Just started with one point and observed as best as possible. I did enjoy this HIT very much, thank you.
I got better as I went on by observing my failures.  I did not understand that an activated node could release more than one signal.

I tried to start clicking the top connection and mark out my first ideas for where that path took me, and then tested other connections to see if they confirmed or refuted my ideas. It was tricky to tell which connections were reacting to which other ones.
Just tried to see what lit up correctly. No real strategy, just paid attention when I tested a connection.
I tried each connection once and follow the activation, it was hard at first but the ones with just three connections were the easiest.

I paid attention to what circle flashed yellow after testing a node. It was alot harder when they had longer delays. I didn't have any particular strategy, I just tried to focus on what node activated the other node, or what didn't. Really liked the game!
I just kept clicking and watching.I found it hard since I am not very good at this type of thing. I just tried to wait to see where they might be according to the directions.

I would test each connection at least once to try and figure out the paths. I found it hard that the paths could go in both directions at the same time, and usually that's where I think I made mistakes on the connections. It was also hard to do more than 3 connections (triangle) for obvious reasons. I didn't spot any bugs or errors that I could see.
Zero bugs worked flawlessly.
I tried to watch and see if the connecting dots flashed at the same time.  If so, I put the connection going both ways.

I tried to click on every component at least once. When it appeared that nothing was moving from a specific component, I would leave that one for last and try to check what connections the other components had. The hardest problem I had was determining which component that connection was coming from but once the answer was shown, it seemed pretty obvious.

At first I did not even understand what it meant when the image showed up with the actual connections and green or red colors.  After a few times, I realized I was doing it right, and that's when I started to get better.  It was easy, we had 6 turns, just click on each point, find out what lights up after it, follow the trail.
I tested different points; if one didn't respond, I figured that was an endpoint, where vectors had to be pointing.  Otherwise I just tried to pay attention at random points to see the correlations.
